column11: The 2018 Major League Baseball postseason kicks off on 2 October with the American League Wild Card game (MLB). The playoffs continue through October leading up to the World Series beginning on 23 October (MLB). See our FAQ to learn about how we resolve questions and how scores are calculated. The Boston Red Sox won the 2018 World Series. This question resolved as "A team from the American League" with an end date of 28 October 2018. See our FAQ to learn about how we resolve questions and how scores are calculated.

column6: Post Mortem: Interestingly, my Brier score is almost identical to the Median. Thus, I didn't add any value to the crowd. My approach was to average between 538 and bettings odds. The betting odds were closer to the eventual truth than 538 and thus I was my Brier is better than somebody who followed 538. Still, that wasn't enough to beat the GJO median. This is in contrast to the FIFA question where following 538 actually led to better-than-median scores. Perhaps this question was an outlier because of the small number of forecasters. Or perhaps one should avoid sports questions if it is hard to consistently beat the median on those due to perhaps the ready availability of great sources like 538.

I have sacrificed a goat, a pig, and a chicken. All the entrails point to the American League. But my tea leaves say National league so I'm going to do a weighted average.

Even without the Philadelphia Athletics, the Washington Senators, and the St. Louis Browns--or maybe especially without them--it looks good for the AL this year. Since I don't approve of expansion teams and the Dodgers belong in Brooklyn, and although there is a special place in hell for whoever thought up the designated-hitter and no-pitch IP rules, I look forward to a Series in which the Red Sox sweep LA. This will almost certainly not happen, but at my advanced age one learns to bear up under disappointments.
AL has advantage in WS historically, and in interleague play. This year is an exception with NL winning interleague, but historically has belonged to AL. Will adjust with postseason outcomes.
